Methane yield of algal–bacterial biomass mainly depends on the biomass composition (lipids, carbohydrates, and proteins) and (ii) the microbial inoculum [29]. The biomass composition changes according to the growing conditions in the ATS system. In our study, the ratio of ash: organic substance varied approximately by 35% between two harvests (July 2.11%, August 1.36%), due to environmental factors, Table 1. The detailed temperature, pH, and solar radiation profiles are given in the Supplementary information 1. The availability of organic substances during anaerobic digestion impacts methane productivity. One approach to increase organic substance in algal–bacterial biomass is the supply of nitrogen-rich wastewater to stimulate growth. Yet, nitrogen limitation increases the synthesis of lipids, fatty acids, or carbohydrates in algae, which can increase methane production [10]. However, in this study, the inoculum had a much greater effect than the substrate, Fig. 4.Fig. 4
